= The <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD**</span> breaks with the coalition

Following a sharp rise in unemployment after Black Thurdays, the unemployment insurance fund has been overstretched and is on the verge of insolvency. To ensure that the unemployed still receive their welfare cheques, we have worked out a compromise with the other centrist parties, in which contribution rates would be increased and welfare slightly cut. However, the <span style="color: #c00000;">**ADGB**</span> and the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD's**</span> intransigent left wing have rejected our compromise and pressure the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD's**</span> national leadership to leave government.
Originally, the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD's**</span> presence in government has been tolerated due to the need for their support for the Young Plan. With the recent ratification of the Young Plan, <span style="color: #808080;">Hindenburg</span> sees no reason to persuade the <span style="color: #c00000;">**socialists**</span> to stay. 

-@expelled

@expelled
title: The <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD**</span> shall leave the coalition. 

With the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD's**</span> exit, the incumbent government no longer holds a majority in the Reichstag and a new cabinet must take its place. Due to Bruning's Christian Nationalist outlook and commitment to fiscal discipline, <span style="color: #808080;">Hindenburg</span> views him as an acceptable candidate for Chancellor and entrusts to him the mandate to broker a cabinet. Now, all we can do is wait and see whether he can survive the vote of no confidence next month.




